default1.1
default              
defaultThe Health Foundation is an independent charity working to improve the quality of healthcare in the UK. Informed by our research and improvement programmes, this submission of evidence 
defaultconsiders 
defaultthe ability of the NHS to ‘
defaulttreat the patient
default as a person’
default and recommends changes
default needed to deliver high quality, person-ce
defaultntred care for people with long-
defaultterm conditions.
default&#xa0;
default1.2
default              
defaultThe NHS has only a very limited ability to deliver person-centred care for people with 
defaultlong-term
default conditions.
default 
defaultThis is because p
defaultatients are largely viewed by clinicians as passive recipients of care and few are supported to develop the skills, confidence and behaviour to effectively manage their conditions. Furthermore, the 
defaultway that the health system is structured and its processes are organised poses a barrier to more person-centred care.
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default              
defaultThe 
defaultvast 
defaultmajority of care for a person with 
defaultlong-term
default conditions is delivered by the individual patient themselves
default because they are living with their condition every day
default. 
defaultIt is therefore essential that 
defaultimprovement of health services 
defaultis 
defaultfocused upon supporting people 
defaultto effectively manage
default their own conditions.
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default              
defaultThere must be
default 
defaultchanges to the roles, mindsets and behaviours of patients and clinicians, supported by processes and infrastructure that enable a new relationship of partnership between people and health professionals.
default&#xa0;
default1.5
default              
defaultTo make the rhetoric of person-centred care a reality, action is required by clinical com
defaultmissioning groups, NHS England 
defaultand those bodies with influ
defaultence on
default the education and training of health professionals.
default&#xa0;
default2default.0default              defaultWhat defaultis person-centred care and why is it important?default&#xa0;
default2
default.1
default              
defaultCoordinated, community-based services are important, but not 
defaulton their own 
defaultsufficient, to deliver sustainable and effective care for people with 
defaultlong-term
default conditions
default. 
defaultThere needs to be a fundamental change in how government a
defaultnd the NHS think
default about care for people with 
defaultlong-term
default conditions. 
default&#xa0;
default2
default.
default2
default              
defaultIt is vital that the improvement of 
defaultlong-term
default conditions management is focused on the role patients themselves can play in effectively managing their conditions. On average, a person with a 
defaultlong-term
default condition spends just three hours each year in contact with a health professional, and that contact does not always coincide with the periods of time when an individual most needs support. 
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default              
defaultPerson-centred care 
defaultshould
default 
defaultsupport people to self-manage, offer personalised care planning and enable people to share in decision making
default.
default It should
default 
defaultuse the 
defaultlimited time patients
default 
defaultspend wi
defaultth a health professional 
defaultto
default:
default enable patients to become knowledgeable, confident managers of their health
default; 
defaultsupport
default people
default with 
defaultlong-term
default conditions
default to make informed decisions about and 
defaultto 
defaultsuccessfully manage their own
default,
default health and 
defaultcare
default; 
defaultdeliver
default care that is responsive to people’s individual abilities, preferences, lifestyles and goals.
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default              
defaultDespite the promotion of these approaches by government and health policy leaders
default,
default truly person-centred care has not spread beyond core innovators. The ability of the NHS to “treat the patient as a person” is far too limited.
default 
default&#xa0;
default2
default.
default5
default              
defaultCreating this person-centred health system
default requires different roles, behaviours and mindsets from clinicians and 
defaultpatients, supported by processes and infrastructure that
default enable new relationship
defaults
default.
default 
defaultHealth professionals need to view people as partners in their care, rather than passive recipients. They need to understand the motivations and challenges that each 
defaultindividual faces in adopting healthy behaviours – not just the biomedical challenges, but psychological and social challenges as well. 
default&#xa0;
default2.6
default              
defaultThis requires 
defaulta 
defaultfundamental shift
default in how health services are delivered, with the emphasis moving 
defaultfrom
default focusing on improving clinical outcomes 
defaultto
default quality of life, 
defaultfrom
default providing specialist treatment 
defaultto
default generic support, and 
defaultfrom
default a system that reacts to people’s ill health to one that focuses proactively on enabling people to live as healthily as possible.
