default&#xa0;
default4
default.2.1
default              
default‘
defaultWe already do that.
default’
default 
defaultThere is a lack of a clear, shared understanding about what effective person-centred care looks like. When urged to participate in our programmes, many health professionals said they already are supporting their patients to self-manage or ar
defaulte using shared decision making.
default 
defaultBut after training sessions, many realised that they had not be
defaulten using a truly person-centred 
defaultapproach.
default&#xa0;
default4
default.2.2
default              
default‘
defaultThere isn’t enough time.
default’
default A common response to our programmes was that health professionals felt they had too much to do and no time to participate in training or 
defaultto 
defaultengage in self-management support and shared decision making. Clinicians also feared that 
defaultthe approaches would
default lengthen the time of consultations.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4
default.2.3
default              
defaultHealth professionals lack understanding about the value of involving patients in design and delivery.
default In Co-creating Health, for example, lay tutors sometimes found that 
defaulthealth professionals
default questioned the role 
defaultpatients 
defaultcould play in clinician training. 
default&#xa0;
default4
default.2.4
default              
defaultHealth professionals are not taught 
defaultskills necessary for person-centred support.
default Our programmes found that few health professionals are equipped with the knowledge and skills necessary to understand what motivates their patients and support them to change behaviours
default.
