default&#xa0;
default5
default.2
default              
defaultChanging culture defaultand behaviours defaultamong health professionalsdefaultHealth professionals need education, training, and development that gives them 
defaultthe 
defaultknowledge and 
defaultskills 
defaultrequired 
defaultfor person-centred care.
default 
defaultThe Health Foundation has learnt the importance of
default the following
default:
default&#xa0;
default5
default.2.1
default              
defaultEncouraging participation in training
default.
default Getting health professionals to participate in training required clearly setting out the benefits of self-management suppo
defaultrt and shared decision making. 
defaultTo address time concerns, t
defaulteams had to adapt training, in some cases shortening the programme or offering mi
defaultni-training
default sessions
default to support staff. 
defaultThose
default who participated found that using shared decision making and agenda setting helped to structure con
defaultsultations
default.
default&#xa0;
default5
default.2.2
default              
defaultTraining whole teams
default. 
defaultCo-creating Health found it important to train whole teams of health professionals from the same service, so that everyone involved had a common understanding of self-management support and its tools and techniques.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5
default.2.3
default              
defaultEnsuring health professionals have the right skills.
default 
defaultTraining involved role playing as well as education in support techniques such as motivational interviewing and coaching skills, which are key to helping patients build confidence.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5
default.3
default              
defaultChanging culture and behaviours among patientsdefaultPatients who attended Co-creating Health group sessions had, on average, become more motivated and confident to self-manage.
default 
defaultAs one person who took the course said: 
default‘
default[I]t galvanised me, it got me going.
default 
defaultI think I pulled myself out of a hole and decided that I was going to do it.
default 
defaultLike the lay person [tutor], she’d obviously taken charge of her illness, and I thought well I can do that, I’m not a wimp
default’.
default 
defaultOur programme
defaults
default helped overcome 
defaultpatient 
defaultbarriers in the following ways
default:
default&#xa0;
default5
default.3.1
default              
defaultEncouraging participation in patient training.
default Co-creating Health found that patients sometimes needed encouragement from a trusted source – especially their GP – 
defaultto prompt them to participate in a training programme.
default&#xa0;
default5
default.3.2
default              
defaultOffering activities
default that build confidence
default.
default 
defaultCo-creating Health 
defaultoffered biomedical, psychological and in some cases socia
defaultl support through peer support.
default Group sessions included goal setting, problem solving, and relaxation, as well as condition-specific training such as self-monitoring or managing pain. Lay and clinical tutors used techniques such as positive psycho
defaultlogy, motivational interviewing
default and helping people identify unhelpful beliefs. 
default5
default.3.3
default              
defaultAdapting to patients’ needs and preferences
default. Teams 
defaultsometimes
default 
defaultchanged 
defaultthe length 
defaultor content of sessions to suit patients
default. 
defaultThey developed creative ways to promote and carry out self-management support, such as through practice-b
defaultased resource libraries or text 
defaultmessages to follow up on goals.
default5
default.3.4
default              
defaultInvolving patients in design and delivery of training sessions
default. Several project managers found that involving pati
defaultents in the design, development
default and implementation of the programmes was vital to meet patients’ needs b
defaultecause the patient perspective ‘could not be imagined’
default by professionals.
default&#xa0;
default5
default.3.5
default              
defaultPromoting peer support
default.
default Peer support at some sites also helped motivate people to engage. Peer support activities ranged from regular phone calls with a 
default‘
defaultbuddy
default’
default, reunions for those who had participated in training together, and a peer-led walking group.
